    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about muscle growth and saw two different terms: mechanical tension and metabolic stress. can you explain the difference between them and which one is actually more important for hypertrophy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension is the force applied to the muscle fibers during resistance training, essentially the strain the muscle experiences under load. Metabolic stress, on the other hand, refers to the buildup of metabolites like lactate within the muscle due to intense training, leading to a \"pump.\" While both contribute to muscle growth, many leading researchers suggest that mechanical tension is the primary driver for hypertrophy. Optimizing heavy, challenging lifts is often considered the most direct way to maximize this tension.",
      "source": "target",
