    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if mechanical tension is the main thing, how does that actually work at the cellular level? like what's happening to the actual muscle fibers when they're under that tension?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "At the cellular level, mechanical tension acts as a signal that tells the muscle fiber to adapt and become stronger. The constant stretching and pulling puts stress on the myofibrils, triggering signaling pathways like mTOR. This pathway is crucial because it stimulates protein synthesis—the process where your body builds new muscle proteins—to repair and reinforce the fibers. Essentially, the tension causes microscopic damage, which the body then overcompensates for by building bigger, stronger muscle tissue.",
      "source": "target",
